As I had hoped, Connecticut testing surged in today’s reporting. Today’s reporting was Connecticut’s highest new test volume for a Tuesday in over six weeks by more than 9,000 tests. I think you could argue that this is a good first sign to come out of the Connecticut colleges reopening story is the priority there currently seems to be on testing.

While, New Cases had recently been on the rise, they seem to be tapering off a bit. This hadn’t been linked to any colleges, and the biggest problem had been in the city of Danbury (John Oliver must have been onto something). That said, it’s worth keeping an eye on.

It’s depressing to see the US having made all that progress only to see it plateau as a new vector or three starts to rage in North and South Dakota as well as Iowa. Iowa’s vector is coming from college towns, and the Dakota’s are coming from Sturgis. All of these were preventable, but here we are. Tests are still showing a downward trend, and are a bit artificially inflated due to a testing audit out of Florida that found several thousand previously unreported new tests.

For now though, the good news is that new deaths are notonly under 1,000 a day, but they are trending downward. This is could be a signal that the tail end of what has been wave two may be bringing those numbers back down. Deaths tend to be a bit of a lagging indicator.
